  "prompt": "Is money laundering subject to legal prosecution?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is subject to legal prosecution in most jurisdictions worldwide. Money laundering is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This practice is illegal because it allows individuals or organizations to profit from criminal activities while concealing the source of the funds.\n\n### Legal Frameworks and Enforcement:\n1. **International Standards**:\n   - Organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** set global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n   - Countries often implement these standards into their national laws.\n\n2. **National Laws**:\n   - Most countries have specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws. For example:\n     - In the **United States**, the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Patriot Act** are key legal frameworks.\n     - In the **European Union**, the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)** provide a unified approach.\n     - In **China**, the **Anti-Money Laundering Law** and related regulations govern this area.\n\n3. **Penalties**:\n   - Penalties for money laundering can be severe and include hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.\n   - Businesses and financial institutions that fail to comply with AML regulations may also face sanctions, including the revocation of licenses.\n\n4. **Investigative Bodies**:\n   - Law enforcement agencies, such as the **FBI**, **Europol**, and **Interpol**, actively investigate and prosecute money laundering cases.\n   - Financial intelligence units (FIUs) in many countries monitor suspicious financial activities and report them to authorities.\n\n### Examples of Prosecution:\n- High-profile cases, such as the **Panama Papers** and **1MDB scandal**, have led to prosecutions of individuals and entities involved in money laundering.\n- Governments often collaborate internationally to track and prosecute cross-border money laundering schemes.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a serious criminal offense that is actively prosecuted under both national and international laws. Individuals and organizations involved in such activities face significant legal consequences.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
